                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 860d.00/178</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Russia</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_FDR1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Francis</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Vologda</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-05-31T19:00:00+02:31">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 31, 1918, 7 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received June 11, 10 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>230. <persName corresp="#p_RCEF1">Riggs</persName> wires 30th that three to four
                    infantry and one cavalry German divisions, also trained Finnish White Guard
                    infantry, are estimated force in Finland, approximating 100,000 men, and great
                    activity in Finnish training camps; also that preparations hastening for attack
                    on Murman line and Murman by construction of railroad for transporting troops
                    which expected to be completed in early July.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_FDR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Francis</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
